05863nam a22008175i 9780857453525DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20122012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2011020657  a97808574535257 a10.1515/97808574535252doi  a(DE-B1597)637496  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aD804.3.N853bC66 2011 7aPER0040302bisacsh00aConcentrationary Cinema :bAesthetics as Political Resistance in Alain Resnais's ‹I›Night and Fog‹/I› /ced. by Griselda Pollock, Max Silverman. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (358 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Plates from Night and Fog -- tList of Figures -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction: Concentrationary Cinema -- t1. Night and Fog: A History of Gazes -- t2. Memory of the Camps: The Rescue of an Abandoned Film -- t3. Opening the Camps, Closing the Eyes: Image, History, Readability -- t4. Resnais and the Dead -- t5. Night and Fog and the Concentrationary Gaze -- t6. Auschwitz as Allegory in Night and Fog -- t7. Night and Fog and Posttraumatic Cinema -- t8. Fearful Imagination: Night and Fog and Concentrationary Memory -- t9. Disruptive Histories: Towards a Radical Politics of Remembrance in Alain Resnais’s Night and Fog -- t10. Cinema as a Slaughterbench of History: Night and Fog -- t11. Death in the Image: The Responsibility of Aesthetics in Night and Fog (1955) and Kapò (1959) -- tBibliography -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince its completion in 1955, Alain Resnais’s Night and Fog (Nuit et Brouillard) has been considered one of the most important films to confront the catastrophe and atrocities of the Nazi era. But was it a film about the Holocaust that failed to recognize the racist genocide? Or was the film not about the Holocaust as we know it today but a political and aesthetic response to what David Rousset, the French political prisoner from Buchenwald, identified on his return in 1945 as the ‘concentrationary universe’ which, now actualized, might release its totalitarian plague any time and anywhere? What kind of memory does the film create to warn us of the continued presence of this concentrationary universe? This international collection re-examines Resnais’s benchmark film in terms of both its political and historical context of representation of the camps and of other instances of the concentrationary in contemporary cinema. Through a range of critical readings, Concentrationary Cinema explores the cinematic aesthetics of political resistance not to the Holocaust as such but to the political novelty of absolute power represented by the concentrationary system and its assault on the human condition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aMemory in motion pictures. 0aMotion picturesxAesthetics. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xMotion pictures and the war. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aDidi-Huberman, Georges, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGladstone, Kay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHebard, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHirsch, Joshua, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLindeperg, Sylvie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMowitt, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPollock, Griselda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPollock, Griselda, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRaskin, Richard, econtributor.4ct